@waltonseymour You may have to look out for two things.
1. If you are composing a fat lib jar to be submitted to druid, make sure you clean the old jars and libs in druid'd hdfs classpath, as the new jars will not overwrite the old jars having the same filename.
2. And as Erik suggested, you have to make sure the version of jackson jars in druid's hdfs classpath or hadoop environment, matches with that of the jars come with druid core. You can tweak your build script by eliminating druid's jackson jars with Exclusion Rules and explicitly adding the required jackson jars.

@xvrl I believe use case @navis has in mind is wanting to store lists where order matters, which would be used by the proposal for storing k/v pairs in #2511 as two multi-value dims (one for keys and one for values). @navis please chime in if there is some other use case you are thinking of too.

At any rate- I'm actually surprised to learn that the current behavior is like a sorted array, I always thought it was like a sorted set!

